This paper is likely to belong to the Computer Vision (cs.CV) sub-category as it deals with the problem of establishing correspondence between shapes, which is a fundamental problem in geometry processing and computer vision. Additionally, the paper introduces a novel convolutional neural network architecture for this purpose. 

The paper may also belong to the Graphics (cs.GR) sub-category as it deals with shape processing and correspondence, which is a common problem in computer graphics. 

The paper's use of deep learning techniques and neural networks makes it likely to belong to the Machine Learning (cs.LG) and Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI) sub-categories. 

Finally, the paper's focus on constructing a set of oriented anisotropic diffusion kernels to generalize convolutions to non-Euclidean domains suggests that it may also belong to the Neural and Evolutionary Computing (cs.NE) sub-category.
